TEM, AFM images, XRD pattern and FTIR spectrum of Fe/B-GQD-HSF were presents at Fig. 2
                        . There are many black dots on the TEM image of Fe/B-GQD-HSF. These black dots could be assigned to graphene sheets, verifying that our synthesis achieves to the formation of 0D graphene sheets. The size of graphene sheets is in the range from 1 to 10 nm with an average size of 4.7 ± 0.2 nm (
                           Fig. s1
                        ). The thickness (h) of graphene sheets is between 0.35 and 3.5 nm (
                           Fig. s2
                        ), indicating the Fe/B-GQD-HSF is composed of one to ten layers of graphene sheets. There is one diffraction peak at about 26° on the XRD pattern of Fe/B-GQD-HSF. The peak is the characteristic (002) crystal of graphene materials [33]. Due to poor crystallinity, the peak at 26° shows weak and wide feature. There are seven IR absorption peaks on the FTIR spectrum of Fe/B-GQD-HSF. The IR absorption peak at 3432 cm−1 is due to the stretching vibration of N–H and O–H bonds. The IR absorption peak at 3144 cm−1 is caused by the stretching vibration of =C–H bond. The IR absorption peak at 1697 cm−1 is caused by the stretching vibration of C=O bond. The IR absorption peak at 1628 cm−1 is due to the stretching vibration of C=C bond [34]. The IR absorption peak at 1400 cm−1 is due to the stretching vibration of C–O bond. The IR absorption peak at 1165 cm−1 is due to the in-plane bending vibration of O–H bond. The above results of IR analysis demonstrates the existence of –OH, –NH–, –COOH and other imidazolyl and aryl groups at the edge of graphene sheets.
